<HEADLINE>
<P>
EDUCATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What short memories we Americans have! When Gen. Douglas MacArthur accepted the 
surrender of Japan on Sept. 2, 1945, one of the terms of surrender required 
Japan to draft a constitution pledged never to rearm again. 
</P>
<P>
Japan accepted our demand, and for the past 40 years has poured its major 
energies, money and resources into educating its young, in the fields of 
science, industry, business management, art and architecture. It is little 
wonder that Japan is attaining world influence in every direction. Japan has 
for two generations invested mainly in its young! It has taken to heart Walt 
Whitman's splendid injunction, "Create great persons. The rest all follows!" 
</P>
<P>
President George Bush wants to be known in history as "the Education 
President." He can be so known, if he makes education his and our highest 
priority, taking to heart Whitman's words, "And you America . . . to girlhood, 
boyhood look, the teacher and the school." 
</P>
<P>
ROBERT STRASSBURG 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
