<HEADLINE>
<P>
IOC DOCTOR CALLS FRANCIS' SABOTAGE THEORY NONSENSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An International Olympic Committee doctor who was in charge of the doping 
control facility at the Seoul Games dismissed the sabotage theory presented in 
testimony by Ben Johnson's coach Charlie Francis, this week at the Canadian 
federal inquiry into drug use in sports. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Manfred Donike of West Germany said Wednesday in an interview with the 
Toronto Star: "I can tell you this is absolute nonsense . . . When I 
interpreted the analytical result of Johnson's urine and took into 
consideration the steroid profile, I saw this was not possible." 
</P>
<P>
Arnold Beckett, an IOC doctor from England, was quoted as saying: "It's a load 
of rubbish, let's face it. First of all, they were talking about someone 
tampering with his bag on the field. Then they started changing it into another 
story about a black man in the waiting room. Then they thought it was a white 
man. Then they mixed the two and got a yellow man. Did he have an antenna, 
too?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
OLYMPIC GAMES (1988); DRUG ABUSE; TRACK AND FIELD; ATHLETES; STEROIDS; JOHNSON, 
BEN; FRANCIS, CHARLIE; DOCTORS; SABOTAGE 
</P>
